Pyotr Kozmich Frolov (Russian: Пётр Козьми́ч Фроло́в; 27 January [O.S. 16 January] 1775 – 22 December [O.S. 10 December] 1839) was a Russian mining engineer and inventor who built the first horse-railway in the Russian Empire in 1809. He elaborated on various canal projects and other artificial water constructions. Frolov also contributed to the development of scientific research and to the culture of the Altay region. His activities as a head of the Kolyvano-Voskresensk factories promoted a great advance of Russian technology in the beginning of the 20th century. He was appointed a senator in 1831.

Summary: 
Pyotr Kozmich Frolov (born January 27, 1775; died December 22, 1839) was a prominent Russian mining engineer and inventor. He is best known for constructing the first horse-drawn railway in the Russian Empire in 1809, as well as working on various canal and water projects. Throughout his career, he contributed significantly to scientific research and the cultural development of the Altay region. His leadership at the Kolyvano-Voskresensk factories advanced Russian technology, and he was later appointed as a senator in 1831.
