Dr Sergey Vasilyevich Goldin (28 January 1936 – 18 May 2007) was a Soviet and Russian geophysicist, Academician of RAS, member of European Academy of Science and American Geophysical Union, director of Institute of Geophysics in Sibiria Branch of RAS (1996- 2004). 
In 1953, S. Goldin has completed secondary school in Vologda with a silver medal award. In the same year he has arrived on geophysical faculty of the Leningrad Mining Institute which has ended in 1958 with the high distinction... In 1991 he has been selected by member-correspondent of the AS USSR, and in 1997 - the full member of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
He was author of more than 200 scientific publication, among which were 4 monographs. Among his pupils are three doctors and 25 holders of PhD of science. S. V. Goldin possesses among others, the theory of the seismic migration allowing quantitatively to compare various algorithms of construction of the plotting of medium and to synthesise algorithms with set properties. Last years the scientist dealt with problems of geophysics new to: experimental and theoretical studying of the nonlinear effects bound to diffusion of seismic waves in heterogenous mediums, studying of physical processes in the seismic source and the forecast of earthquakes. 
Awards: State Prize of the Russian Federation (1998) Order of Friendship (2006)
He died on 18 May 2007 after a serious illness, and is buried at the Cherbuzinskoye Cemetery in Novosibirsk.

Summary: 
Sergey Vasilyevich Goldin (January 28, 1936 – May 18, 2007) was a prominent Soviet and Russian geophysicist, an Academician of the Russian Academy of Sciences (RAS), and director of the Institute of Geophysics in the Siberian Branch of RAS (1996-2004). Educated at the Leningrad Mining Institute, he earned a doctorate and became a professor, making significant scientific contributions to the field of geophysics. He authored over 200 scientific publications and is renowned for developing the theory of seismic migration, studying the non-linear effects of seismic waves, and proposing innovative concepts for geodynamic monitoring and earthquake prediction involving mesostructures. For his work, he received the State Prize of the Russian Federation in 1998 and the Order of Friendship in 2006.
